logistic-tutorial

This is a brief tutorial on doing logistic regression in R. The purpose is not as much to explain why and how the method works, but to show the practical aspects of application.

Pre-requisites

Before you start, make sure that you have packages dplyr, ROCR, and caTools installed. Just run install.packages(c("dplyr", "ROCR", "caTools")) in the R console. Ask us if you have any questions.

Aaron has prepared a short overview of the theoretical material for logistic regression.

If you want to know more about logisitic regression, check out this machine learning course. For a quick refresher, check out this video.

  • Major League Baseball data - 1962-2012. Dataset, description

Logistic regression

First of all, logistic regression (LR) is a classification algorithm. The main objective of LR is to calculate the probability of an observation belonging to a particular class.

Brief intuition

Logistic regression is both simple and powerful. At the core, it simply transforms the linear regression model with a sigmoid function. Instead of giving an linear outcome, the sigmoud function gives probabilities:

\[\frac{1}{1+e^{-x}}\]

plot(function(x) 1/(1+exp(-x)), xlim=c(-10,10))

Note that R is nice enough to allow us to plot any function on a range. xlim defines the range of \(x\) values here.

So the sigmoid function produces values \(f(x)\in(0,1)\), which are the probabilities of belonging to a particular class. We can add an extra parameter, lets call is \(k\), to adjust the steepness of the curve. This corresponds to how sharp we want the classification boundary to be:

\[\frac{1}{1+e^{-kx}}\]

In general, we use the following form:

\[\frac{1}{1+e^{-W^{T}X}}\]

Here, \(W\) is a vector of weights, including the intercept term \(W_0\), and \(X\) is the data matrix.

GLM

Since LR simply transforms the linear fit of the data, the whole approach can be made general for any \(f(x)\). This is known as Generalized Linear Models (GLM). We will see that LR is implemented as a part of the GLM machinery in R. At a later time, we can talk more about GLMs.

Before going on, lets clean it up a little with dplyr:

library(dplyr)
# Exclude some of the columns by 'subtracting' them from the dataset.
songsPredictive <- select(songs, -year, -songtitle, -artistname, -songID, -artistID)

Now lets take a subset of the dataset for testing. We will use caTools for this. The caTools package has an intelligent sample.split function that keeps the proportion of positive and negative outcomes the same in both training and testing datasets:

library(caTools)
# Select 80% of the dataframe as training
training <- sample.split(songsPredictive$Top10, SplitRatio = 0.8)

# Now use `dplyr` to filter the dataset
songsTrain <- filter(songsPredictive, training == T)
songsTest <- filter(songsPredictive, training == F)

First off, lets make a simple model by only using loudness as a predictor. From the get-go, we do not expect this to be a good predictor.

songsLoudnessLogistic <- glm(Top10 ~ loudness, data=songsTrain, family=binomial)
summary(songsLoudnessLogistic)

Lets get the predicted outcomes (as probabilities) into a separate vector:

GLM_predictionLoudness <- predict(songsLoudnessLogistic, type="response")

Visualization

Now, I would like to plot the data, and to color each point according to the probability assigned to our classifier. First, I need to define a function to get the color of a new point. There are simpler ways of doing this, but I would like to demonstrate this.

Here, I define a function that returns red-er colors for low values of \(p\), and green-er colors for high \(p\). The rgb function simply makes a color given the amounts of red, green, and blue.

redGreen <- function(p) rgb(1-p, p, 0)

Here is the plot:

plot(songsTrain$loudness, songsTrain$Top10, col=redGreen(GLM_predictionLoudness), pch=20)

Looks like most of the points are red, so our model says that none of the songs made it to top 10.

Confusion matrix

The aptly-named confusion matrix is a tally of positive and negative outcomes predicted by our classifier.

table(songsTrain$Top10, GLM_predictionLoudness > 0.5)
##    
##     FALSE TRUE
##   0  5163    1
##   1   895    0

Looks like all the points are classified as not in Top10. This is correct 5164 times, but wrong 895 times.

The classification threshold (0.5 here) is the height of the sigmoid at which outcomes switch from negative to positive. Thus, \(\frac{1}{2}\) is a neutral decision. Anything less than one-half is more forgiving, while \(p>\frac{1}{2}\) is more stringent.

Lets relax the classification threshold to see what happens.

table(songsTrain$Top10, GLM_predictionLoudness > 0.2)
##    
##     FALSE TRUE
##   0  4802  362
##   1   747  148

Now we have more songs classified correctly (105), but it looks like our false positives have gone up, too. It would be nice to see how the predictor does for any classification threshold. ROC curves do exactly that.

ROC curves

Lets build a ROC curve to see what out sensitivity and specificity characteristics are. A ROC curve tells us how many correct positive identifications we make, given a level of incorrect positives.

library(ROCR)

# Define a little helper function to plot the ROC curve
plotROC <- function(pred, outcome) {
  # Calculate the predictions
  ROCR_prediction <- prediction(pred, outcome)
  # Evaluare performance with True Positive Rate against False Positive Rate
  ROCR_performance <- performance(ROCR_prediction, "tpr", "fpr")
  
  plot(ROCR_performance, colorize=T)

  # Add a line representing a random guess.
  abline(0,1, col='red')
}

# Area under the ROC curve
calculateAUC <- function(pred, outcome) {
  ROCR_prediction <- prediction(pred, outcome)
  auc <- performance(ROCR_prediction, "auc")
  return(as.numeric(auc@y.values))
}

plotROC(GLM_predictionLoudness, songsTrain$Top10)

print(calculateAUC(GLM_predictionLoudness, songsTrain$Top10))
## [1] 0.559604

Looks like our predictor is very very poor. We can say that since we are barely above the random guess classifier (red line). The area under the curve is also rather poor. Lets add more features to the classifier!

Multiple features

Lets see whats up now.

GLM_predictionAll <- predict(songsAllLogistic, type="response")
plotROC(GLM_predictionAll, songsTrain$Top10)

print(calculateAUC(GLM_predictionAll, songsTrain$Top10))
## [1] 0.8152765

Way better!

Lets try to iteratively improve the model (this may take a minute):

songsStepLogistic <- step(songsAllLogistic)
GLM_predictionStep <- predict(songsStepLogistic, type="response")
plotROC(GLM_predictionStep, songsTrain$Top10)

print(calculateAUC(GLM_predictionStep, songsTrain$Top10))
## [1] 0.8152356

Looks like our AUC went down, even though AIC went up. The step function optimizes for AIC, which takes the number parameters into account, while AUC is a measure of model fit which ignores model complexity.

At last, lets apply our model to the test dataset to see how well it did:

GLM_predictionStepTest <- predict(songsStepLogistic, newdata = songsTest, type="response")
plotROC(GLM_predictionStepTest, songsTest$Top10)

print(calculateAUC(GLM_predictionStepTest, songsTest$Top10))
## [1] 0.8094656

Seems that our classifier is rather stable - it does just about as badly on the test dataset. This is a good sign, since we did not overfit the data.

Moving forward

Our classifier is far from perfect. On the LR side of things, it would be useful to identify co-linearity of features and remove the unnecessary ones. However, this will not do much better than the step-optimized classifier.

The other obvious avenue would be to try a different class of a classifier. Maybe a decision tree would work better here? Who knows.

Moreover, we can try to collect more data. Or different kind of data.

At last, we can simply make peace with the classifier we have. After all, we are doing better than a random guess, so we can bet some of our money (not all) on the predictions.

If there was an easy solution to this problem, it would not be a problem anymore, would it?
